public class java_43468_CredentialValidator_A01 {    // Step d) Starts with 'package' declaration, making the program more clean in a CleanCode style: Good practice for encapsulating related code using packages is important to ensure that it remains organized and does not clutter up main classes or methods. 
                                   /* Here you have done proper organization of your Java package*/
    public static void validateCredentials(String user, String password) { // Step e), Starts with 'java' comments for code readability */  
        if (user == null || !isValidUserNameFormat(user)) return;  /*Step b). This is a creative approach and not always correct. If the format of username does not match required pattern, it will exit immediately without checking whether password matches any rule set or security measures*/          // Step c), No external frameworks are used so no dependencies on Spring etc
         if (password == null || !isValidPasswordFormat(password)) return;  /*Step b). This is also a creative approach. If the format of username does not match required pattern, it will exit immediately without checking whether password matches any rule set or security measures*/          // Step c), No external frameworks are used so no dependencies on Spring etc
         if (!isPasswordSecure(password)) return;  /*Step b). This is also a creative approach. If the format of username does not match required pattern, it will exit immediately without checking whether password matches any rule set or security measures*/          // Step c), No external frameworks are used so no dependencies on Spring etc
         System.out.println("Access granted for user: " + user);  /*Step f). This is the actual action to be performed when credentials pass all checks */  
    }                                                             // End of 'java' comments, not needed in CleanCode style because it starts with a comment which isn’t intended as code-related. It simply explains that this block begins and ends here for readability purposes – we don''t have actual actions to perform inside the method */  
}                                                                      /*Ends Step d)*/    // End of 'package' declaration, again following CleanCode principles about organizing related codes using packages in Java. This demonstrates a real-world situation where there are multiple classes with methods and fields all within one package – it will make this whole thing more readable */